'''Marion Tournon-Branly''' (born 23 September 1924) is a [[France|French]] [[architect]]. She was born in Paris to architect [[Paul Tournon]] and painter <U+00C9>lisabeth Branly (daughter of [[Edouard Branly]]). After studying at the [[<U+00C9>cole nationale sup<U+00E9>rieure des Beaux-Arts]], she collaborated with her father and with [[Auguste Perret]].

[[File:Paul Tournon et Marion Tournon-Branly.jpg|thumb|Marion Tournon-Branly and her father, 1956]]
She designed villas, elementary schools, buildings for the [[Fleury Abbey]] and the modern church of the [[Fontenelle Abbey]].<ref>''Le Don de l'architecture. Paul Tournon, Marion Tournon-Branly'', French National Archives, Fontainebleau, 2013 (exhibition booklet)</ref>

